Here is an article about my clarinet-cello-piano trios.\par
\par
{\f2\b A Clarinetist\rquote s Journey of the Spirit \u160 ? by Joe Rosen\par }
\par
(printed in The Clarinet magazine, September 2007)\par
\par
\tab\ldblquote What music is this?\u160 ? Chamber music with clarinet, sure, but by whom?\rdblquote\u160 ?\par
\par
\tab Radio reception in the Pennsylvania mountains fades, recovers, then fades again, exasperating drivers.\u160 ? Fear of missing the announcer\rquote s tag forced me to pull over and wait for the coda.\u160 ? Finally came the revelation:\u160 ? Rick Sowash.\u160 ? New to me.\u160 ? I made note and hightailed it home to New York City.\par
\par
\tab A Google later I learned that I had heard one of no less than fifteen trios for clarinet, cello and piano by this 57-year old Cincinnati composer. \u160 ? Among my best friends are a cellist and pianist.\u160 ? I thought, why not? and ordered the sheet music directly from the composer at his website.\par
\par
\tab My cellist and pianist friends joined me twice a week, for seven weeks and played through all the trios in the order in which they were written, an extraordinary journey.\u160 ? Then we played them through all over again, thrilled to find memorable tunes, rich tonal harmonies, intricate counterpoint and an astonishing variety of moods, ranging from humor to tragedy.\par
\tab \par
\tab These trios were written during the past eight years for the composer\rquote s French friends, \ldblquote les Gavottes,\rdblquote  a Riviera-based professional trio.\u160 ? They recorded the first three on their CD \ldblquote Enchantement d\rquote avril\rdblquote  and have performed a half dozen of the trios, most notably at the Cannes Film Festival.\u160 ? Les Gavottes have not found time to perform or even read all the music Sowash has written for them; my friends and I are the first musicians to play through all of Sowash\rquote s trios.\par
\par
\tab The first trio is entitled \ldblquote Journey of the Spirit,\rdblquote  a title which might apply collectively to\u160 ? these fifteen works.\u160 ? Its four movements proceed from a darkly mysterious opening in A minor, through a Romantic interlude in G major, to a probing plainchant in E major, to a Hallelujah-like finale in Eb major.\u160 ? It\rquote s a journey from doubt to faith.\par
\par
\tab Trio #2, Enchantment of April, gives a nod to the life-affirming Miramax film of a few years back entitled \ldblquote Enchanted April.\rdblquote\u160 ? We\rquote re in Bb and Eb major and it\rquote s all sweetness and light.\par
\par
\tab The zig-zag pattern of these trios is apparent in the contrasting Trio #3, Shadows of November in A minor.\u160 ? The outer movements invite rough, energetic playing while the middle movement, a farewell to Autumn, is some of the saddest music we\rquote ve ever played.\par
\par
\tab There are some challenging licks in these trios, but virtuoso display is not what this music is about.\u160 ? Solid intermediate players can easily handle most of the trios.\u160 ? Expressivity is what\rquote s required.\par
\par
\tab Conversation of the Trees is the subtitle for #4, in D minor, offering five movements of lively \lquote chatter\rquote  between the three instruments, which are made of wood, after all, and wood comes from trees, right?\u160 ? Here the trees \ldblquote speak.\rdblquote \par
\par
\tab Trio #5, \ldblquote in classical style,\rdblquote  takes up the vocabulary of Haydn-through-Schubert, but with an American twist.\u160 ? The key is G minor, the minuet is tongue-in-cheek, the variations on an original American-sounding hymn-tune are colorful and funny and touching.\u160 ? All of the major themes of the first three movements recur in the rollicking Finale.\par
\par
\tab Again by sharp contrast comes the lengthy Trio #6, Goddess of the Moon, with a Debussy-like atmosphere, impressionistic and ambiguous, and cast in the gorgeous key of Db major.\u160 ? The movements are entitled:\u160 ? Prologue, Nocturne, Interlude, Scherzo and Epilogue.\u160 ? We performed this trio in concert and found that audiences want to applaud after the rousing Scherzo, thinking the piece has ended.\par
\par
\tab It\rquote s a zig-zag again from lush, long #6 to short, snappy, funny #7 \ldblquote The Philosopher Visits a Country Fair\rdblquote  in one movement.\u160 ? In A major, this one reminded us of Bernstein\rquote s Candide Overture.\u160 ? The country fair bubbles along in changing meters while the grumpy philosopher is depicted by a noble, pompous hymn-tune in 3/4.\u160 ? The two musics are then combined and get along beautifully.\par
\par
\tab Self-portraits are usual for painters, rare among composers.\u160 ? Trio #8 offer Two Self-portraits, both in Eb minor.\u160 ? First \ldblquote as a fool,\rdblquote  a clunky, hilarious four-part round with a\u160 ? contrasting pastoral section in C major.\u160 ? Then the deeply felt, \ldblquote as a sage\rdblquote  with a C major middle section once again, this time with a starry-night feel.\par
\par
\tab From self-portrayal, the composer moved to portraying \ldblquote Five Women\rdblquote  in Trio #9 in F major.\u160 ? They are the women in the composer\rquote s life and his movement titles describe the ladies thus:\u160 ? Merry & Mystical, In the Process of Becoming, Mother of My Children, Beautiful & Sad, and The Vitality of Emilie.\u160 ? This is the trio with the greatest variety of styles.\par
\par
\tab The next two trios are lighter and easier.\u160 ? \ldblquote Winds of May\rdblquote  is #10 in Bb major, with movements entitled Morning, Deep Forest, Wildflowers and Sunset.\u160 ? #11 in G major is a nostalgic remembrance of good times, entitled \ldblquote We Sang, We Danced.\rdblquote  \u160 ? The last movement is a very funny Tango, the only one in all the trios.\par
\par
\tab The longest and most challenging trio is #12 in Eb major, \ldblquote Voyageurs,\rdblquote  an epic homage to Canada.\u160 ? The first movement, \ldblquote Geese in Flight,\rdblquote  captures the V-formation flight pattern of Canada geese with a figure that rises in the clarinet while falling simultaneously in the cello.\u160 ? \ldblquote Song of the Voyageurs\rdblquote  evokes the hardiness of the French trappers with what sounds like a Breton folksong.\u160 ? Canada\rquote s natural wonders are depicted in the last two movements:\u160 ? \ldblquote Starshadows on Snow\rdblquote  and \ldblquote A Majestic Land.\rdblquote\u160 ? This music has a Sibelius-like orchestral breadth and ambition.\par
\par
\tab Thirteen is famously the unlucky number.\u160 ? Trio #13 in Eb minor, though a joy to play, is alternately sad and furious.\u160 ? The two movements, Passacaglia and Fugue, are played with hardly a pause between them, since the fugue subject grows right out of the Passacaglia tune.\u160 ? Indeed, at the height of the fugue, the Passacaglia tune recurs in the bass while the couterpoint rages overhead.\u160 ? This trio is boldly \lquote dedicated to the victims of Bush and Bin Laden,\rquote  a mournful, angry response to current events.\par
\par
\tab There are two un-numbered trios, both chamber transcriptions of orchestral works.\u160 ? \ldblquote The View from Carew,\rdblquote  originally a rhapsody in Eb major for clarinet and orchestra, evokes the sublime view of the Ohio Valley that is to be seen atop Carew Tower, the tallest building in Cincinnati. \u160 ?\par
\par
\tab The other and most recent trio is a transcription of the composer\rquote s new Concerto for Cello and Strings with Clarinet, written in the Fall of \lquote 06.\u160 ? It\rquote s a cello concerto alright, but the clarinet seems unwilling to accept this and constantly tries to upstage the soloist.\u160 ? As in trio #7, the key is A major and the score calls for the A clarinet.\u160 ? After the dark anger of #13 and the deep sighs of \ldblquote Carew\rdblquote  the mood finally turns joyful again in this final trio.\u160 ? The four movements are:\u160 ? Hymns & Fugues, Bulgarian Blues, Sorbet (a 28-second bagatelle) and the improbable Finale, written in the Reggae/Dixieland style known as \lquote Ska.\rquote \par
\par
\tab I\rquote ll admit to being a little obsessed with this composer but the rewards of playing his music are very great.\u160 ? Part of the fun, for me, was that, when I started playing his music, almost no one seemed to have heard of him.\u160 ? That\rquote s changing.\u160 ? Kalin Ivanov premiered his cello concerto in Carnegie Hall in April, \lquote 07.\u160 ? Rick met Kalin in my apartment while attending a home concert of his music which I had organized.\par
\par
\tab In discovering these trios and the many other Sowash clarinet works (36 in all) we\rquote ve also made a friend.\u160 ? Rick has attended and emceed performances we\rquote ve done in Manhattan, Long Island, Cleveland, Cincinnati and Waterloo, Ontario.\u160 ? He\rquote s even written two works specifically for me:\u160 ? Three Bagatelles for Clarinet & Bassoon and \ldblquote Audubon,\rdblquote  his only wind octet.\par
\par
\tab It\rquote s been a Journey of the Spirit.\u160 ? And it all started with a half-heard broadcast in the mountains of Pennsylvania.\par
\par
